Overview

I attended RStudio’s conference this year in Orlando, Florida. The conference had 400 attendees representing an incredibly diverse group of companies and industries. Professionals from financial services had a strong showing. I met BI analysts, portfolio managers, risk analysts, and others from a range of firms involved in asset management, banking, and insurance. Beyond finance, I met data scientist and analysts from companies involved in everything from life sciences, advertising, ancestry research, consulting, and beyond.

All of this is to say that the utility of R as an analysis and reporting platform is clearly a compelling value proposition to an extremely wide range of individuals and firms. Open-source principles of transparency and reproducibility came up in almost every session.

Open-Source software is durable. It is durable in that it is not tied to a given corporate entity’s success or failure, it will outlive even the corporate entities which sponsor it. And therefore, as an individual creator, its more rewarding to work on because there is an opportunity to have this permanent lifetime. Also I think, from the standpoint of users, that is actually one of the most important things about R, you know your investment in it is not actually tied to any company, and you know your investment is durable.
J.J. Allaire, CEO of R Studio

RStudio’s Multi-Pronged Approach

RStudio may be best known for their leading IDE, but their vision for the modern data science environment goes beyond one standalone tool. RStudio has a well-defined vision and reliable execution for three key phases of enterprise data analysis. The RStudio IDE is a platform for reproducible data analysis, R Markdown and Shiny are frameworks for authoring data-driven content, and RStudio Connect provides the publishing platform needed for an enterprise to deploy all of this content.

Ultimately, I would classify RStudio’s business strategy vectors into three main categories:

  1. Bringing tried-and-true software development best practices to data science
  2. Utilizing the power and flexibility of web technology to empower data communications
  3. Using R as an interface across a much larger world of software tools

RStudio IDE

RStudio is a platform for transparent, audit-able, reproducible data analysis based in the R computing environment. RStudio’s eponymous product comes in 2 flavors, desktop and hosted, with an open-source and commercial option for each. Kevin Ushey, lead engineer on the IDE, gave a talk “What’s New in the IDE” (slides here) which showcased a range of features to maximize R programmers productivity. From intelligent auto-completion to project-wide file and function search, it is clear to me that RStudio has a deep understanding of what it is really like to be an R programmer.

In another session, RStudio engineer Jon Mcpherson spoke about “RStudio Server Pro Power Tools” (slides here). RStudio Server provides a wide range of features targeted at enterprise concerns including scalability, auditing and monitoring, logging, load-balancing, pair programming, enhanced security, and remote access.

I have been an avid RStudio user for 2 years and am consistently impressed by their pace of development, and more importantly, the relevance and usefulness of the features they add to the application. I’ve yet to come across another IDE that adds so much value to the development process. The open-source, community-centric ethos of RStudio places their finger squarely on the pulse of the data community.

R Packages

Hadley Wickham, Chief Scientist at RStudio, kicked off the conference with a keynote on doing data science in R. The theme of his talk was “Solve complex problems by combining simple, uniform pieces.” This idea naturally lends itself to Lego metaphors, which were heavily used across the entire weekend. Hadley’s talk focused on the tidyverse, which is RStudio’s core set of open-source R packages for various steps of the data analysis pipeline. He also focused on the notion of splitting your code into commands that do something, as opposed to queries that calculate something. RStudio the person at the keyboard as the bottleneck in most processes, and so RStudio is focused on making humans as productive as possible.

RStudio is working on a wide range of R packages that support and enhance the ecosystem. A big area of focus is data source connectivity. Click here for the slides from the “Database Best Practices” talk. R already has connectivity for about every data type you could name, but RStudio is actively developing a number of solutions for even more robust database functionality. RStudio’s connectivity packages are enterprise-centric, with many options for navigating the issues around scaling database powered applications. Engineers said to look out for Reusable Connections functionality to be built into the GUI soon.

R Markdown Reports & Beyond

If RStudio (the IDE) is the platform for developing analyses, and the tidyverse is the grammar of those analyses, then R Markdown is the report writer solution in RStudio’s portfolio. In reality, it can do much more than a traditional report writer. R Markdown is RStudio’s enhanced version of the well known markdown language. Markdown is a lightweight human-readable markup language to create formatted documents. R Markdown supports dozens of static and dynamic output formats including HTML, PDF, MS Word, HTML5 Slide decks, books, dashboards, websites, blogs, and more. Any analysis or visualization that can be produced in R can be embedded in an R Markdown report. Click here for a bunch of samples of R Markdown reports. This write-up is an example itself! The biggest strength of R Markdown is its transparency and reproducibility. There is no ambiguity in the process that generates a report because all of the logic, calculations, and report design itself are right in the source file.

Flexdashboard is a framework for creating web dashboards using R Markdown…this was new to me and WOW do they make it easy to create stunning data-driven content.

Shiny Apps

Where R Markdown is the RStudio solution for creating data-driven content, Shiny is the RStudio solution for data-enabled/data-driven applications. Shiny is an R package which provides a framework for creating fully functioning applications driven by HTML, CSS, and JavaScript. These three languages provide the backbone for the majority of modern applications and web interfaces. These apps have access to the entire world of R capabilities, and as such can be built to solve just about any data-related problem.

RStudio Connect

RStudio seems to have a solution to create any type of report or data product we could need. The question becomes, what do we do with them now? RStudio officially announced their enterprise publishing platform, RStudio Connect, at rstudio::conf(2017). RStudio Connect is a centralized platform for the hosting and distribution of any data-driven content made in R/RStudio. R programmers can deploy their content from their IDE to RStudio Connect with the push of a button. Content deployed to RStudio Connect is initially only available to the publisher. Once deployed, you can set up access restrictions, tune performance, schedule reruns, and view logs from within the RStudio Connect dashboard.

Closing Comments

I come away from the 2017 RStudio conference supremely confident in R as a platform and RStudio as a key vendor for taking advantage of that open source platform. As the official recordings of talks become available, I will be sure to pass them along.
